			<text id="header" x="225" y="15" width="225" height="" autosize="H" style="PANEL_HEADER" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">Language Development</content>
			</text>
			<text id="text" x="225" y="40" width="367" height="" autosize="H" style="PANEL" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Language development is the basis for literacy and&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt; is strongly tied to children’s growth in both reading &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;and writing. &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;To achieve literacy, children must first acquire many basic concepts and strategies such as:&lt;/P&gt;&lt;LI&gt;An awareness of the sounds that make up language &lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;An ability to rhyme syllables and words&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;A familiarity with print materials &lt;/LI&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Researchers have found that perhaps the most &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;significant factor in determining children’s reading &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;success is their oral language skill.&lt;/P&gt;</content>
			</text>
